## Vercel Speed Insights Installation

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights for the whoop-lens Next.js application.

### Changes Made

**1. Package Installation:**
- Installed `@vercel/speed-insights` version 2.0.0 using pnpm
- Added dependency to `package.json`
- Generated `pnpm-lock.yaml` lockfile

**2. Code Integration:**
- Modified `apps/web/src/app/layout.tsx`:
  - Added import: `import { SpeedInsights } from "@vercel/speed-insights/next";`
  - Added `<SpeedInsights />` component at the end of the `<body>` tag (after ReportProvider)
  - Fixed import ordering to comply with Biome linter rules (third-party imports before Next.js imports)

**3. Verification:**
- ✅ Build completed successfully with `pnpm run build`
- ✅ Linter passed with `pnpm run lint` (no errors)
- ✅ All 41 tests passed with `pnpm run test`
- ✅ No regressions introduced

### Implementation Details

Following the official Vercel Speed Insights documentation (fetched from https://vercel.com/docs/speed-insights/quickstart), I used the Next.js App Router integration method since this project uses:
- Next.js 16.2.2 (App Router)
- TypeScript
- React 19.2.4

The `SpeedInsights` component from `@vercel/speed-insights/next` was added to the root layout to enable speed monitoring across all pages. The component will automatically track Core Web Vitals and other performance metrics when deployed to Vercel.

### Next Steps

To complete the setup:
1. Deploy the application to Vercel
2. Navigate to the Vercel dashboard and enable Speed Insights for the project
3. Verify that speed metrics are being collected after deployment

No additional configuration or environment variables are required.
